    content: `
<p>Most people think estate planning is something you do when you're wealthy, old, or both. The truth is that if you have assets, dependants, or people who would be affected by your death — you need a plan.</p>

<p>Without a valid will, your estate is distributed according to the Intestate Succession Act. That may not reflect your wishes. Your family could wait months — sometimes over a year — for assets to be released. And without proper planning, estate duty and executor's fees can consume a significant portion of what you leave behind.</p>

<h3>The Basics Everyone Needs</h3>

<p><strong>A valid will.</strong> Simple, signed, witnessed correctly. Without it, the state decides what happens to your assets.</p>

<p><strong>Nominated beneficiaries.</strong> Life policies, retirement funds, and TFIs all allow you to nominate beneficiaries directly. These assets bypass your estate entirely — meaning faster payout and no executor's fees on that portion.</p>

<p><strong>Liquidity planning.</strong> Your estate may be asset-rich but cash-poor. Life cover can ensure your family has immediate cash flow while the estate winds up.</p>

<h3>Estate Duty in South Africa</h3>

<p>Estate duty applies at 20% on the dutiable estate above R3.5 million (R7 million for married couples). Proper structuring — including trusts for larger estates — can reduce this significantly.</p>

<p>A straightforward will costs very little to set up. The cost of not having one is far higher. <a href="contact.html" style="color:var(--green); font-weight:600;">Get in touch</a> and we'll make sure your estate is in order.</p>
